  "prompt": "What is the best free web hosting provider?",
  "response": "Choosing the best free web hosting provider depends on your specific needs, such as the type of website you want to create, the level of support you require, and any potential limitations you can tolerate. Here are some popular free web hosting providers that are well-regarded:\n\n1. **InfinityFree**: Offers unlimited disk space and bandwidth with no ads. It supports PHP and MySQL, making it suitable for dynamic websites. However, it may have some limitations on server resources.\n\n2. **000webhost**: A popular choice that provides a free plan with limited disk space and monthly bandwidth. It has a user-friendly control panel and offers features like website builders and support for PHP and MySQL.\n\n3. **Freehostia**: Offers a free hosting plan with limited resources (disk space and bandwidth). It includes a website builder and supports PHP and MySQL, making it suitable for smaller projects.\n\n4. **GitHub Pages**: Great for hosting static websites. If you\u2019re a developer or familiar with Git, you can easily deploy websites directly from your GitHub repositories. It\u2019s free and supports custom domains.\n\n5. **Netlify**: Similar to GitHub Pages, Netlify is specifically tailored for static sites and can be integrated with a variety of static site generators. It offers continuous deployment and is known for its ease of use.\n\n6. **WordPress.com**: Ideal for bloggers and content-driven sites. The free plan includes a subdomain and basic features, but upgrades are available for more customization and additional features.\n\n7. **Wix**: Offers a free plan that allows you to build websites using a drag-and-drop interface. It includes Wix branding on your site but is great for quick projects or personal websites.\n\n8. **Weebly**: Another option for building websites through a drag-and-drop builder. The free version has limitations like storage and Weebly branding but is user-friendly.\n\nRemember that while free web hosting can be a great way to get started, it often comes with limitations such as bandwidth restrictions, storage limits, and lack of customer support. Consider upgrading to a paid service if your website grows or requires more resources.",
